<div id="review_1217286095" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1217286095" />
    <a title="Jess the Shelf-Declared Bibliophile" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2744708-jess-the-shelf-declared-bibliophile"><img alt="Jess the Shelf-Declared Bibliophile" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606058182p2/2744708.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1217286095?book_show_action=true">Mar 03, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jess the Shelf-Declared Bibliophile" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jess the Shelf-Declared Bibliophile" href="/user/show/2744708-jess-the-shelf-declared-bibliophile">Jess the Shelf-Declared Bibliophile</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780385682824" href="/book/show/20890479-the-love-song-of-miss-queenie-hennessy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1217286095" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2897476306521193769">Ugh. ugh ugh ugh. I really shouldn&apos;t have given this a shot, considering I only gave the first one 3.5 stars. The author made the characters in this book completely unlikeable, and even more so loathable. In the first book, I enjoyed their friendship. I liked the characters and how they found solace in each other in an innocent way. The way the second book was written feels like the author was grasping for another success, Unsuccessfully. It was way too easy for her to make Queenie in love with </span>
  <span id="freeText2897476306521193769" style="display:none">Ugh. ugh ugh ugh. I really shouldn't have given this a shot, considering I only gave the first one 3.5 stars. The author made the characters in this book completely unlikeable, and even more so loathable. In the first book, I enjoyed their friendship. I liked the characters and how they found solace in each other in an innocent way. The way the second book was written feels like the author was grasping for another success, Unsuccessfully. It was way too easy for her to make Queenie in love with Harold, and it completely took away every ounce of likeability that Queenie had garnered in the first book. Queenie was pathetic in this book, spending her entire life mooning over a man who was devoted to his family. She went way too far with spending so much time with his son, that was almost creepy as well. There was no positive character development or anything, in fact the characters actually seemed to develop negatively. The only thing I liked was the story of the hospice home life, but it wasn't enough to make me glad I read the book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2897476306521193769" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


